# Section 4 — Key Findings

## Finding 1 — Departmental Turnover

The Sales department demonstrated the highest employee turnover rate at approximately 34%, which is significantly above the company average of 21%. Production and Customer Support departments also showed elevated termination rates, indicating potential concerns related to workload, employee engagement, or management practices.

---

## Finding 2 — Time-to-Hire Analysis

The average company-wide time-to-hire was 39 days. Technical and IT-related departments required the longest hiring periods, averaging between 48–55 days, likely due to specialized skill requirements and limited candidate availability.

---

## Finding 3 — Recruitment Source vs Employee Performance

Employees recruited through LinkedIn and employee referrals consistently achieved higher performance ratings compared to hires sourced through generic job portals. Referral hires showed stronger long-term performance consistency and lower absence rates.

---

## Finding 4 — Highest Quality Recruitment Sources

Employee referral programs produced the highest-quality hires, with an average employee satisfaction score of 4.3/5 and higher participation in special projects. Online job boards generated the highest application volume but lower overall employee retention and satisfaction scores.

---

## Finding 5 — Termination Predictors

Employees with high absenteeism and lower engagement survey scores were significantly more likely to be terminated. Certain positions within Sales and Operations also experienced disproportionately higher termination counts, suggesting possible role-specific challenges.

